# Finding Common Elements Without Extra Data Structures

The constraint "no extra data structures" means we can't use a `HashSet`, additional arrays, or lists to store intermediate results. We'll rely only on **nested loops** and direct comparison (O(1) extra space).

## Approach 1: Brute Force (Nested Loops)

Compare every element of the first array with every element of the second.

### Java
```java
public class CommonElements {
    public static void findCommon(int[] arr1, int[] arr2) {
        System.out.print("Common elements: ");
        for (int i = 0; i < arr1.length; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j < arr2.length; j++) {
                if (arr1[i] == arr2[j]) {
                    System.out.print(arr1[i] + " ");
                    break; // avoid printing the same element twice
                }
            }
        }
        System.out.println();
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int[] arr1 = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5};
        int[] arr2 = {3, 5, 7, 9, 1};
        findCommon(arr1, arr2);  // Output: 1 3 5
    }
}
```

### Python
```python
def find_common(arr1, arr2):
    print("Common elements:", end=" ")
    for i in range(len(arr1)):
        for j in range(len(arr2)):
            if arr1[i] == arr2[j]:
                print(arr1[i], end=" ")
                break  # avoid duplicate prints
    print()

arr1 = [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]
arr2 = [3, 5, 7, 9, 1]
find_common(arr1, arr2)  # Output: 1 3 5
```

**Complexity:** Time `O(n × m)`, Space `O(1)`

---

## Approach 2: Sort + Two Pointers (More Efficient)

If you're allowed to modify (sort) the input arrays in place, this is faster.

### Java
```java
import java.util.Arrays;

public class CommonElementsSorted {
    public static void findCommon(int[] arr1, int[] arr2) {
        Arrays.sort(arr1);   // in-place, no extra structure
        Arrays.sort(arr2);

        int i = 0, j = 0;
        System.out.print("Common elements: ");
        while (i < arr1.length && j < arr2.length) {
            if (arr1[i] == arr2[j]) {
                System.out.print(arr1[i] + " ");
                i++;
                j++;
            } else if (arr1[i] < arr2[j]) {
                i++;
            } else {
                j++;
            }
        }
        System.out.println();
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        findCommon(new int[]{1, 2, 3, 4, 5}, new int[]{3, 5, 7, 9, 1});
    }
}
```

**Complexity:** Time `O(n log n + m log m)`, Space `O(1)` (ignoring sort's internal stack)

---

## Which to choose?

| Scenario | Best Approach |
|----------|---------------|
| Small arrays / strict "no modification" rule | Brute Force |
| Large arrays / sorting allowed | Sort + Two Pointers |
| Need handling of duplicates | Add a check to skip equal adjacent elements in Approach 2 |

